WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.060
 So now we're going to start building things with gates.

00:00:03.060 --> 00:00:05.680
 Gates are our new low-level building blocks.

00:00:05.680 --> 00:00:07.460
 So the first thing we're going to do

00:00:07.460 --> 00:00:09.880
 is add some numbers with gates.

00:00:09.880 --> 00:00:12.520
 And we're going to basically use a pattern much like this,

00:00:12.520 --> 00:00:16.580
 except that this little adding hand calculator

00:00:16.580 --> 00:00:18.480
 does numbers from zero through nine.

00:00:18.480 --> 00:00:21.560
 We're gonna do the same thing with just zero and one,

00:00:21.560 --> 00:00:23.280
 so they're gonna do base to addition,

00:00:23.280 --> 00:00:25.840
 but we're still gonna do things like carry.

00:00:25.840 --> 00:00:28.160
 So when we click over to the next one,

00:00:28.160 --> 00:00:31.480
 it carries and goes on to the next number.

00:00:31.480 --> 00:00:33.720
 And so we're gonna solve the carry problem.

00:00:33.720 --> 00:00:37.100
 At this point, you should know the truth tables

00:00:37.100 --> 00:00:40.200
 for not an and, an or, and exclusive or.

00:00:40.200 --> 00:00:42.640
 Now, not an and and or are kinda like

00:00:42.640 --> 00:00:45.480
 what you've done in programming for a long time now.

00:00:45.480 --> 00:00:47.000
 Exclusive or is just kinda weird,

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:50.520
 meaning that it's more of a counter than a simple or,

00:00:50.520 --> 00:00:53.480
 which means if one of them is true, the output is true,

00:00:53.480 --> 00:00:57.160
 and if both are zero or both are one, the output is zero.

00:00:57.160 --> 00:00:59.640
 And of course, nand and nor

00:00:59.640 --> 00:01:02.080
 are just kind of inverted versions of and and or.

00:01:02.080 --> 00:01:04.520
 So at this point, I think you should be able to

00:01:04.520 --> 00:01:07.200
 fill these in, and I probably won't need

00:01:07.200 --> 00:01:09.300
 to explain these to you much more.

00:01:09.300 --> 00:01:13.720
 But we do wanna represent numbers larger than zero and one.

00:01:13.720 --> 00:01:16.600
 That would be kind of a limited range.

00:01:16.600 --> 00:01:20.200
 So what we use is we use base two numbers,

00:01:20.200 --> 00:01:22.920
 and we take different wires and give them different values.

00:01:22.920 --> 00:01:26.160
 And so in base two, there's a one's position,

00:01:26.160 --> 00:01:29.480
 a two's position, a four's, and an eight's position.

00:01:29.480 --> 00:01:33.400
 And so you can think of three wires can represent a number

00:01:33.400 --> 00:01:36.160
 from zero through seven.

00:01:36.160 --> 00:01:41.160
 So in base 10, 123 is one times 100, two times 10,

00:01:41.160 --> 00:01:45.600
 and three times one, which adds up to 123,

00:01:45.600 --> 00:01:47.360
 which is kind of redundant.

00:01:47.360 --> 00:01:50.240
 But if you look at base two, one, one, zero,

00:01:50.240 --> 00:01:53.200
 that's one times four, which is four,

00:01:53.200 --> 00:01:56.480
 plus one times two, which is two,

00:01:56.480 --> 00:01:58.580
 plus zero times one, which is zero,

00:01:58.580 --> 00:02:00.160
 four plus two equals six.

00:02:00.160 --> 00:02:04.000
 So to convert one, one, zero base two into base 10,

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:05.740
 it's six base 10.

00:02:05.740 --> 00:02:07.440
 We're gonna make things simple for now.

00:02:07.440 --> 00:02:10.280
 We're not gonna make you generally be able to convert

00:02:10.280 --> 00:02:11.860
 any base 10 number.

00:02:11.860 --> 00:02:15.160
 As a matter of fact, for most of the rest of this section

00:02:15.160 --> 00:02:18.400
 of the class, we will never encounter a number

00:02:18.400 --> 00:02:20.480
 higher than zero through eight.

00:02:20.480 --> 00:02:23.680
 Mostly it will be zero through seven, and then once in a while

00:02:23.680 --> 00:02:25.960
 we'll carry into the eight's position.

00:02:25.960 --> 00:02:29.320
 So we represent the four's position, the two's position,

00:02:29.320 --> 00:02:30.760
 and the one's position.

00:02:30.760 --> 00:02:32.800
 So one, one, zero equals six.

00:02:32.800 --> 00:02:35.640
 But you can quickly say, oh, that's a four, that's a two,

00:02:35.640 --> 00:02:38.300
 and no one, which is four plus two equals six.

00:02:38.300 --> 00:02:42.500
 So you can quickly convert from that.

00:02:42.500 --> 00:02:45.600
 So the idea of having one wire represent

00:02:45.600 --> 00:02:49.360
 the ones of a number, another wire representing

00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:51.980
 the two's of the number, and another wire representing

00:02:51.980 --> 00:02:54.800
 the four's of the number, is how we can represent

00:02:54.800 --> 00:02:57.620
 a number from zero through seven.

00:02:57.620 --> 00:03:00.000
 So in this example that I've given you,

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:03.200
 the two's wire is a one, and the four's wire is a one,

00:03:03.200 --> 00:03:06.320
 and we hook that to a Nixie tube.

00:03:06.320 --> 00:03:07.660
 Remember Nixie tubes?

00:03:07.660 --> 00:03:13.040
 The Nixie tube decodes the ones, two's, and four's,

00:03:13.040 --> 00:03:15.000
 and converts it to base 10.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:19.720
 So if we're putting in zero ones, one two's, and one four's,

00:03:19.720 --> 00:03:21.360
 well that's two plus four equals six.

00:03:21.360 --> 00:03:24.520
 And the Nixie tube has the logic to simply display that.

00:03:24.520 --> 00:03:28.040
 So if we can send it a set of wires, three wires,

00:03:28.040 --> 00:03:30.320
 it will show us the base 10.

00:03:30.320 --> 00:03:33.960
 And in order to help you have a good understanding

00:03:33.960 --> 00:03:36.840
 of quick conversion from base two to base 10,

00:03:36.840 --> 00:03:39.520
 at least for numbers between zero and seven,

00:03:39.520 --> 00:03:42.080
 I've got a little game called the Nixie Challenge

00:03:42.080 --> 00:03:45.800
 that both converts base two to base 10, base 10 to base two,

00:03:45.800 --> 00:03:48.400
 and adding of base two numbers.

00:03:48.400 --> 00:03:50.800
 Now speaking of adding base two numbers,

00:03:50.800 --> 00:03:53.360
 let's start at the very beginning.

00:03:53.360 --> 00:03:55.820
 One plus one equals two.

00:03:55.820 --> 00:03:59.200
 That's true in base 10, but it's not true in base two.

00:03:59.200 --> 00:04:01.480
 'Cause you don't have the digit two in base two.

00:04:01.480 --> 00:04:05.840
 So one plus one is zero, carry the one.

00:04:05.840 --> 00:04:09.880
 Just like five plus five is, in base 10,

00:04:09.880 --> 00:04:12.880
 is zero, carry the one, or 10.

00:04:12.880 --> 00:04:15.960
 So one zero base two is two because that's a one

00:04:15.960 --> 00:04:18.880
 in the two's position and a zero in the one's position.

00:04:18.880 --> 00:04:23.360
 So remember, one plus one equals zero, carry the one.

00:04:23.360 --> 00:04:26.240
 You see the same pattern when you do two plus two

00:04:26.240 --> 00:04:28.920
 equals four, zero plus zero equals zero,

00:04:28.920 --> 00:04:31.360
 one plus one equals zero, carry the one.

00:04:31.360 --> 00:04:32.760
 And again, the same thing happens

00:04:32.760 --> 00:04:34.360
 when you do four plus four equals eight.

00:04:34.360 --> 00:04:38.040
 And so now we've seen our first number greater than seven.

00:04:38.040 --> 00:04:39.800
 Four plus four equals eight.

00:04:39.800 --> 00:04:43.100
 Now you gotta carry, you gotta ripple carry

00:04:43.100 --> 00:04:45.600
 in the three plus one equals four example.

00:04:45.600 --> 00:04:48.360
 One plus one equals zero, carry the one.

00:04:48.360 --> 00:04:51.160
 Now in the second column, you gotta add that carry.

00:04:51.160 --> 00:04:55.120
 The carry one plus the top one equals zero, carry the one.

00:04:55.120 --> 00:04:58.440
 So now we end up with one, zero, zero, or four.

00:04:58.440 --> 00:05:01.600
 And so these carries can cruise along.

00:05:01.600 --> 00:05:02.800
 Three plus two equals five.

00:05:02.800 --> 00:05:05.980
 You can see there's a one plus zero equals one.

00:05:05.980 --> 00:05:08.140
 One plus one equals zero, carry the one,

00:05:08.140 --> 00:05:11.200
 which gives us one, zero, one, which is a four and a one,

00:05:11.200 --> 00:05:12.400
 which is five.

00:05:12.400 --> 00:05:15.200
 And then the last one, which is seven, all ones,

00:05:15.200 --> 00:05:18.400
 which is a four plus a two plus a one, which is seven.

00:05:18.400 --> 00:05:23.400
 Seven plus one, you start with one plus one equals zero,

00:05:23.400 --> 00:05:26.560
 carry the one, but then the carry plus the other one

00:05:26.560 --> 00:05:29.320
 is zero again, carry the one again,

00:05:29.320 --> 00:05:31.800
 and then the carry plus the one is a zero,

00:05:31.800 --> 00:05:35.400
 carry the one again, and then you end up with the one.

00:05:35.400 --> 00:05:39.300
 So seven plus one equals eight.

00:05:39.300 --> 00:05:43.880
 So the logic that we do here to do one of these columns,

00:05:43.880 --> 00:05:48.880
 so just the columns, is a thing we call the half adder.

00:05:48.880 --> 00:05:54.240
 And half adder is a logic circuit that takes as its inputs

00:05:54.240 --> 00:05:56.800
 the A and the B, and as output,

00:05:56.800 --> 00:05:59.120
 comes up with the sum and the carry.

00:05:59.120 --> 00:06:02.160
 Now for now, we're only thinking about one column

00:06:02.160 --> 00:06:06.040
 of addition, zero plus zero is zero, carry the zero.

00:06:06.040 --> 00:06:08.520
 Zero plus one is one, carry the zero.

00:06:08.520 --> 00:06:11.120
 One plus zero equals one, carry the zero.

00:06:11.120 --> 00:06:13.920
 One plus one equals zero, carry the one.

00:06:13.920 --> 00:06:16.040
 So if we look at the circuit,

00:06:16.040 --> 00:06:20.400
 the circuit is a combination of the and and an exclusive or.

00:06:20.400 --> 00:06:22.640
 And if you look at the two columns,

00:06:22.640 --> 00:06:25.480
 you look at the sum column, the sum column,

00:06:25.480 --> 00:06:29.440
 zero, one, one, zero, is just the same as a close of or,

00:06:29.440 --> 00:06:32.320
 and the carry column is just the same as the and.

00:06:32.320 --> 00:06:34.000
 So we simply take the A and the B,

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:36.960
 both to an exclusive or gate and both to an and gate,

00:06:36.960 --> 00:06:40.080
 and out comes a sum and a carry.

00:06:40.080 --> 00:06:43.120
 So two gates gives us a half adder.

00:06:43.120 --> 00:06:44.960
 So if we look at the different values,

00:06:44.960 --> 00:06:49.640
 zero plus zero equals zero, carry the zero.

00:06:49.640 --> 00:06:52.960
 One plus zero equals one, carry the zero.

00:06:52.960 --> 00:06:56.720
 And one plus one equals zero, carry the one.

00:06:56.720 --> 00:07:00.120
 So this solves one column of addition.

00:07:00.120 --> 00:07:01.880
 But if you think about one column of addition

00:07:01.880 --> 00:07:05.280
 other than the first column, there's also a carry in.

00:07:05.280 --> 00:07:08.840
 And that's how we solve it with the full adder.

00:07:08.840 --> 00:07:12.560
 So the full adder, its truth table has a carry in,

00:07:12.560 --> 00:07:17.400
 a sum A, sum B, and then a sum total and a carry out.

00:07:17.400 --> 00:07:21.840
 So operands A and B, a carry in, sum and carry out.

00:07:21.840 --> 00:07:25.000
 So if you get a carry in, that's a one.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:27.280
 If you get an A of one and a B of one,

00:07:27.280 --> 00:07:31.880
 well that is three, which is the sum is one, carry the one.

00:07:31.880 --> 00:07:33.800
 So that's a little different, right?

00:07:33.800 --> 00:07:35.960
 So now we have up to three numbers.

00:07:35.960 --> 00:07:39.280
 It's kind of like a counter of three bits, right?

00:07:39.280 --> 00:07:41.320
 And it's showing us that.

00:07:41.320 --> 00:07:44.040
 But we have a carry in, A and B,

00:07:44.040 --> 00:07:46.400
 and then a sum and a carry out, okay?

00:07:46.400 --> 00:07:49.420
 And so it's pretty much what you would expect.

00:07:49.420 --> 00:07:52.200
 You can think of the sum and the carry out as like,

00:07:52.200 --> 00:07:54.320
 the carry out is kind of like a two.

00:07:54.320 --> 00:07:56.520
 When you're carrying to the next column, okay?

00:07:56.520 --> 00:07:58.640
 So let's take a look at the circuit

00:07:58.640 --> 00:08:01.040
 that needs to solve this problem.

00:08:01.040 --> 00:08:04.920
 A full adder compensates for a carry in.

00:08:04.920 --> 00:08:07.480
 So we call a full adder, a full adder

00:08:07.480 --> 00:08:11.400
 because it really is two half adders plus a little bit.

00:08:11.400 --> 00:08:15.360
 So if you look at the section that's the A and the B,

00:08:15.360 --> 00:08:16.640
 that's just a half adder.

00:08:16.640 --> 00:08:18.880
 It's got an exclusivore and an and.

00:08:18.880 --> 00:08:23.440
 And then what we have is another half adder at the top,

00:08:23.440 --> 00:08:26.280
 exclusivore two and and two.

00:08:26.280 --> 00:08:30.720
 And the input to that half adder is the carry in

00:08:30.720 --> 00:08:33.560
 plus the output of exclusivore one.

00:08:33.560 --> 00:08:36.520
 Exclusivore two produces the overall sum

00:08:36.520 --> 00:08:38.040
 of the three numbers.

00:08:38.040 --> 00:08:39.760
 And then we have to add an or gate

00:08:39.760 --> 00:08:42.960
 that takes the output of the A and B and,

00:08:42.960 --> 00:08:44.800
 as well as the and,

00:08:44.800 --> 00:08:46.660
 and we or it all together and get a carry out.

00:08:46.660 --> 00:08:48.640
 And you can look at that or as,

00:08:48.640 --> 00:08:51.800
 did we generate a carry out by A and B?

00:08:51.800 --> 00:08:56.800
 Or did we generate a carry out because A or B was one

00:08:56.800 --> 00:08:58.200
 and the carry in was one?

00:08:58.200 --> 00:08:59.760
 And that's what that or is doing.

00:08:59.760 --> 00:09:02.560
 So it's probably best to take a quick look

00:09:02.560 --> 00:09:04.520
 at how this works with a working circuit.

00:09:04.520 --> 00:09:07.460
 So here is a full adder circuit.

00:09:07.460 --> 00:09:10.840
 And so we're gonna start and work through carry in,

00:09:10.840 --> 00:09:14.980
 A and B, and then the sum and the carry out.

00:09:14.980 --> 00:09:17.480
 So we're set them all to zero, so the sum is zero.

00:09:17.480 --> 00:09:21.440
 So let's just exercise this as a half adder, for example.

00:09:21.440 --> 00:09:23.240
 So if we make A be one,

00:09:23.240 --> 00:09:27.080
 then we get a sum of one and a carry out of zero.

00:09:27.080 --> 00:09:29.100
 And if we make B be one,

00:09:29.100 --> 00:09:32.920
 then we get a sum of zero and a carry out of one.

00:09:32.920 --> 00:09:35.800
 And so the carry in is not participating in any way.

00:09:35.800 --> 00:09:39.280
 This is just a half adder that's working.

00:09:39.280 --> 00:09:41.740
 So now if we add the carry in,

00:09:41.740 --> 00:09:44.700
 so now we have carry in of one,

00:09:44.700 --> 00:09:46.620
 A of one, B of one,

00:09:46.620 --> 00:09:48.940
 and sum is one and carry out is one.

00:09:50.640 --> 00:09:51.760
 And now you can pretty much

00:09:51.760 --> 00:09:53.800
 put any combination of ones and zeros,

00:09:53.800 --> 00:09:56.060
 and this is kind of a counter

00:09:56.060 --> 00:09:58.720
 where the carry out plus the sum is like how many?

00:09:58.720 --> 00:10:02.180
 Carry in is one and A is zero and B is one.

00:10:02.180 --> 00:10:03.840
 We kind of have two ones,

00:10:03.840 --> 00:10:06.020
 and so we get a carry out of one and a sum of zero.

00:10:06.020 --> 00:10:10.780
 That's kind of one zero, which is a two, okay?

00:10:10.780 --> 00:10:12.440
 So that's a full adder.

00:10:12.440 --> 00:10:17.280
 It's basically two half adders plus an OR gate.

00:10:17.280 --> 00:10:19.200
 Now that we built this full adder,

00:10:19.200 --> 00:10:22.320
 and we won't go into too much detail here,

00:10:22.320 --> 00:10:25.200
 but this carry out was designed

00:10:25.200 --> 00:10:27.860
 to become the carry in for the next digit.

00:10:27.860 --> 00:10:31.360
 So if we look at two plus five equals seven,

00:10:31.360 --> 00:10:33.400
 we can see that the full adder

00:10:33.400 --> 00:10:37.760
 has the A for the ones column and the B for the ones column,

00:10:37.760 --> 00:10:40.120
 A for the twos column and B for the twos column,

00:10:40.120 --> 00:10:43.280
 and A for the fours column and B for the fours column.

00:10:43.280 --> 00:10:48.520
 And so because A is two, A one is zero,

00:10:48.520 --> 00:10:52.760
 A two is one, and A four is zero, so zero one zero.

00:10:52.760 --> 00:10:55.320
 B is five, and so it's one zero one.

00:10:55.320 --> 00:10:59.920
 So B one is one, B two, the twos column of B is zero,

00:10:59.920 --> 00:11:02.320
 and the fours column of B is one.

00:11:02.320 --> 00:11:04.200
 And so they just go into these full adders,

00:11:04.200 --> 00:11:06.040
 and when we say full one in here,

00:11:06.040 --> 00:11:09.740
 that is those gates that we just got done describing.

00:11:09.740 --> 00:11:13.880
 And they have a sum out, and that goes to our ultimate sum,

00:11:13.880 --> 00:11:15.880
 but the carry out of each column

00:11:15.880 --> 00:11:18.640
 goes to the carry in of the next column.

00:11:18.640 --> 00:11:20.960
 That's what's clever about the full adder.

00:11:20.960 --> 00:11:22.840
 So this is a ripple carry.

00:11:22.840 --> 00:11:26.680
 The carry is rippling from one column to the next.

00:11:26.680 --> 00:11:28.980
 On the screen, it's the top to the bottom.

00:11:28.980 --> 00:11:31.440
 So you just copy, you connect the carry outs

00:11:31.440 --> 00:11:33.440
 to the carry in of the next full adder.

00:11:33.440 --> 00:11:36.460
 And then that full adder has a carry out, and away it goes.

00:11:36.460 --> 00:11:38.480
 Now if you look at the third one,

00:11:38.480 --> 00:11:41.580
 you have the carry out that indicates an overflow indicator,

00:11:41.580 --> 00:11:45.480
 and that is this can only handle numbers from zero through seven,

00:11:45.480 --> 00:11:49.320
 but if you add five plus five, that's bigger than seven,

00:11:49.320 --> 00:11:51.240
 and the overflow indicator.

00:11:51.240 --> 00:11:53.160
 We're like, oh, now we just figured out

00:11:53.160 --> 00:11:58.040
 how to take three full adders and make a three-bit adder.

00:11:58.040 --> 00:11:59.440
 So this is a three-bit adder

00:11:59.440 --> 00:12:04.160
 with the A's on the left-hand side, zero, one, zero, or two,

00:12:04.160 --> 00:12:07.760
 and the B's on the right-hand side, one, zero, one, or five.

00:12:07.760 --> 00:12:09.920
 And you can see the adder has a seven.

00:12:09.920 --> 00:12:12.000
 We put a little display in there

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:14.140
 so you can see the number seven,

00:12:14.140 --> 00:12:15.920
 and it has sums coming out the bottom,

00:12:15.920 --> 00:12:19.040
 and it has overflows coming out the top.

00:12:19.040 --> 00:12:22.540
 And so this is part of how digital logic works,

00:12:22.540 --> 00:12:27.240
 is that we build something cool, like a three-bit adder

00:12:27.240 --> 00:12:30.700
 that's made up of three full adders,

00:12:30.700 --> 00:12:33.280
 which each full adder is made up of two half adders

00:12:33.280 --> 00:12:35.720
 plus an OR gate, but we don't have to draw that.

00:12:35.720 --> 00:12:39.160
 We just say, give me a three-bit adder, and away you go.

00:12:39.160 --> 00:12:42.180
 And so we can quickly build abstractions

00:12:42.180 --> 00:12:46.040
 that are all really cool, reusable componentry.

00:12:46.040 --> 00:12:50.360
 And so we only build a full adder long enough

00:12:50.360 --> 00:12:52.320
 to build a three-bit adder

00:12:52.320 --> 00:12:55.000
 to build then a three-bit adder component.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:57.440
 And so we can build these things pretty rapidly,

00:12:57.440 --> 00:12:59.520
 and now you can start to see

00:12:59.520 --> 00:13:02.840
 how we might eventually build a microprocessor.

00:13:02.840 --> 00:13:05.360
 At least now we have a three-bit adder.

00:13:05.360 --> 00:13:06.560
 And if you listen carefully,

00:13:06.560 --> 00:13:08.680
 maybe go back and watch this again,

00:13:08.680 --> 00:13:12.480
 if you look at it carefully, you'll see, you know,

00:13:12.480 --> 00:13:15.760
 if you go all the way back, you know how many transistors

00:13:15.760 --> 00:13:18.080
 that you could make a three-bit adder,

00:13:18.080 --> 00:13:19.640
 but it would be a bunch of 'em.

00:13:19.640 --> 00:13:21.120
 It would be a bunch of 'em.

00:13:21.120 --> 00:13:24.160
 'Cause remember, an AND gate is

00:13:24.160 --> 00:13:29.720
 four transistors plus the NOT, which is two transistors.

00:13:29.720 --> 00:13:32.200
 So an AND gate is six transistors,

00:13:32.200 --> 00:13:33.680
 and that's just an AND gate.

00:13:33.680 --> 00:13:37.720
 So you figure out after a while that building gates

00:13:37.720 --> 00:13:40.080
 and then building reusable components,

00:13:40.080 --> 00:13:41.760
 you know how to build 'em,

00:13:41.760 --> 00:13:44.240
 but you don't have to know how to build 'em

00:13:44.240 --> 00:13:48.800
 to use a component like a three-bit adder in a circuit.

00:13:48.800 --> 00:13:50.320
 And that's the fun of it all.

00:13:50.320 --> 00:13:53.320
 And we're gonna keep doing this as we go forward.

00:13:53.320 --> 00:13:55.900
 (upbeat music)

